---
import DocsLayout from '../layouts/DocsLayout.astro';

const sections = [
  { label: 'What Bedrock Is', href: '#what-bedrock-is' },
  { label: 'Layer Map', href: '#layer-map' },
  { label: 'Implemented Tools', href: '#implemented-tools' },
  { label: 'Documentation Rules', href: '#documentation-rules' }
];
---

<DocsLayout
  title="sf-bedrock technical docs"
  description="Technical documentation for the sf-bedrock Salesforce architecture toolkit."
  eyebrow="Overview"
  sections={sections}
>
  <Fragment slot="header">
    <h1>Build cleaner Salesforce automation.</h1>
    <p class="lede">
      sf-bedrock is a base layer for stable Apex architecture: dependency injection
      for data access and DML, efficient tests, trigger hygiene, and service
      patterns that keep enterprise automation understandable.
    </p>
  </Fragment>

  <section class="doc-section" id="what-bedrock-is">
    <h2>What Bedrock Is</h2>
    <p>
      Bedrock gives Salesforce teams a small set of predictable framework seams.
      Production code stays direct and readable, while tests can replace DML,
      query behavior, cache access, and staged trigger work without building a
      heavy test harness.
    </p>
    <div class="callout">
      <strong>Design principle</strong>
      <p>
        Start with the implemented library in <code>force-app/bedrock/lib</code>.
        Roadmap topics should be marked clearly until the API exists.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="doc-section" id="layer-map">
    <h2>Layer Map</h2>
    <p>
      The architecture separates record lifecycle automation from reusable query
      logic, UI adapters, and service coordination. The docs should make those
      boundaries visible before diving into individual classes.
    </p>
    <div class="doc-grid">
      <article class="doc-card">
        <h3>Domain</h3>
        <p>Triggers and record lifecycle behavior live here, coordinated by small handlers.</p>
      </article>
      <article class="doc-card">
        <h3>Selector</h3>
        <p>Query logic belongs behind reusable selectors that build on <code>Query</code>.</p>
      </article>
      <article class="doc-card">
        <h3>Service</h3>
        <p>Cross-record orchestration and meaningful business behavior belong in services.</p>
      </article>
      <article class="doc-card">
        <h3>UI Layer</h3>
        <p>Controllers should adapt component needs and delegate meaningful complexity.</p>
      </article>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="doc-section" id="implemented-tools">
    <h2>Implemented Tools</h2>
    <p>
      The first documentation pass should focus on the APIs already present in
      the library. That gives readers a reliable path before introducing planned
      Selector, Async, Event, Scheduler, or LimitsService work.
    </p>
    <ul class="token-list">
      <li>
        <strong>TestData</strong>
        <span>Builds mockable or insertable records with focused field setup and generated Ids.</span>
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>DML</strong>
        <span>Centralizes DML through an injectable service and captures operations in tests.</span>
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Query</strong>
        <span>Provides a static facade over virtual query behavior for predictable data access tests.</span>
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>RecordBuffer</strong>
        <span>Stages inserts and updates during trigger flows so services can cooperate safely.</span>
      </li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section class="doc-section" id="documentation-rules">
    <h2>Documentation Rules</h2>
    <p>
      Each page should name the production contract, show the smallest useful
      example, and call out test behavior. Keep roadmap notes separate from
      shipped APIs so developers can trust what they read.
    </p>
    <div class="utility-panel">
      <div>
        <h3>Next page</h3>
        <p>
          Use the starter guide to document how to run the docs locally and how to
          choose the first API page.
        </p>
      </div>
      <a class="button button-primary" href="/getting-started">Getting Started</a>
    </div>
  </section>
</DocsLayout>
